<TEXT>
an irish man imprisoned here for seven years in 
an immigration dispute testified tuesday that hes quit the irish 
republican army and would abide by all bail conditions if released 
joseph doherty 35 faces a life sentence in the united kingdom 
for the 1980 slaying of a british officer doherty escaped from a 
belfast prison in 1981 and fled to the united states on the orders 
of an ira superior he was captured here in 1983 and has been held 
in a manhattan jail since 
at a bail hearing doherty said he would return to the united 
kingdom if his bid for political asylum in the united states fails 
if i were to go back to face the hangmans rope i would go 
back doherty said during four hours of testimony i would pay 
my own ticket and gladly go back go back graciously on that plane 
with no malice to the united states 
doherty has fought extradition to britain since his arrest 
he has acknowledged that the british officer was killed in a 
gunfight between troops and his fourman ira unit but claims the 
fighting was political and that he would be persecuted if forced to 
return 
us district judge miriam g cedarbaum is considering a request 
that doherty be freed on an 800000 bail package pending 
resolution of the asylum request 
his say his right to due process has been violated by his 
lengthy imprisonment 
dohertys plight has become a rallying point among 
irishamericans here he has been honorary grand marshal of the st 
patricks day parade and has a manhattan street named for him the 
courtroom was filled with supporters tuesday including three 
congressman and several local politicians 
cedarbaum sought dohertys testimony to help decide whether he 
is a flight risk 
the us government which opposes his release will present 
witnesses at a later hearing after which cedarbaum will rule 
doherty testified that he resigned from the ira when he came to 
the united states and has had no contact with its members 
the armed group is fighting to wrest northern ireland from 
british rule and unite it with the irish republic 
even if the ira wanted him i would refuse to go back to them 
because of my commitment to the court and the provisions of bail 
and also to these people in the back doherty said my life is 
minuscule compared to the irishamerican community 
however us attorney otto obermaier sought to discredit 
doherty stressing his use of a false passport to enter the united 
states and a false social security number to get work 
a federal appeals court ruled this summer that doherty has the 
right to seek asylum here 
</TEXT>
