<TEXT>
the 265th quartermaster detachment of the south 
carolina national guard is one of the reserve units called up for 
possible duty in saudi arabia national writer fred bayles is 
following this small unit of 14 guardsmen as they prepare for 
deployment overseas 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
when 22 members of the grahamharris 
family assembled to sing happy birthday to the family patriarch 
their celebration site was an unlikely one a bustling army post 
preparing for possible war 
there was no choice two key family members are part of that 
preparation 
don graham and henry harris are brothersinlaw who belong to 
the 265th quartermaster detachment a south carolina national guard 
unit getting ready for deployment to the mideast 
the water purification unit has been at fort stewart training 
hard since thursday as a reward the men got labor day afternoon 
off so most of the mens families made the twohour drive from 
their homes around allendale sc where the unit is based 
harris wife sister and brothers were there graham had the 
biggest turnout a caravan of brothers and sisters their children 
and five of his own seven children the guest of honor was his 
father earnest graham who turned 83 on tuesday 
don graham a 37yearold construction supervisor joined the 
guard with his brotherinlaw 17 years ago he accepts his 
assignment to the mideast with little emotion its something we 
got to do he said 
he said he is proud of his children and wants to see them grow 
up but he said he doesnt spend time worrying about less pleasant 
possibilities 
you cant predict life you could go out the door and get 
killed he said something like this makes you appreciate life 
more 
graham and the other unit members couldnt go off post so they 
gave their relatives a limited tour of the military complex an 
extended visit to the px and lunch at a fastfood franchise 
the families also got a glimpse of the units accommodations a 
long barracks of cinder block and wood built to sleep 40 
the quarters are kindly described as spartan no water dim 
overhead bulbs and little ventilation it bakes during the day and 
retains the heat well into the night 
the men have spread out over the big barracks taking bunks in 
clusters that describe the dynamics of the group 
three sergeants occupy the far end and gather most nights to 
play guts an aptly named card game of bluffing and side bets they 
play for quarters now but back in allendale they are joined by 
other friends each friday night for games of much bigger stakes 
sometimes we have 10 people sitting around the table said 
hullie cohen a burly contractor 
the men joke with their wives about going to bed at 8 pm they 
make tentative plans to see each other again depending on the 
units status what they dont talk about is the mideast and their 
likely deployment 
the men hardly talk about it among themselves when they do it 
is usually to joke about the heat 
some have suggested landscapers be sent in ahead of the unit to 
plant shade trees others suggest just a little more seriously 
that they sell the water they will purify to the saudis at prices 
equivalent to gasoline 
in conversations some say they are eager to go others wish 
they could go back home there is little mention of political 
issues there is an absence of bravado 
on their second day of mobilization the unit went to a post 
orientation meeting with a larger group of florida reservists 
called up to work at the post hospital 
as the session was ending a lieutenant colonel asked the 265th 
to stand up these men he told the 200 other reservists were on 
their way to the mideast 
these are your friends and neighbors just up the road he 
said this is a great outfit 
the rest of the hall burst into applause the 14 men from 
allendale exchanged grim nervous glances mostly they looked down 
at their feet 
</TEXT>
