<TEXT>
teachers with computer skills are turning their 
classrooms into models of education reform tailoring lessons to 
meet students individual needs in subjects from french to science 
a new study finds 
the firstofitskind survey of 608 computersavvy teachers in 
576 schools across the country found that many have learned ways to 
individualize lessons and teach more sophisticated material using 
computers 
the survey released monday by the bank street college of 
educations center for technology in education found teachers 
using computers in ways that go far beyond the usual 
drillandpractice 
more than 9 out of 10 said they use word processors for writing 
lessons as many as twothirds produced readymade art and more 
than 70 percent used terminals for problemsolving programs 
drillandpractice lessons especially in math or tutorial 
programs 
more than half the social studies teachers surveyed 52 percent 
used computers to construct databases 
i think that its very clear that what these teachers have 
accomplished is exactly the kinds of things people engaged in 
reform are trying to accomplish said karen sheingold director 
of the center and coauthor of the report with bank street 
researcher martha hadley 
eightyeight percent believe their computer knowledge has 
transformed classroom life they have higher expectations of their 
students present more complex material and believe their students 
are gaining better thinking skills 
but teachers also complained of having too few computers 
printers and other hardware and scarce time to plan and conduct 
computer lessons 
the report recommended that schools rethink their schedules so 
that teachers have the time they need 
teachers taking part in the mailed survey conducted in the 
spring of 1989 taught grades 4 through 12 in all 50 states they 
were identified as knowledgeable about computers by computer and 
software companies and education groups 
spreading the classroom computer revolution is possible but 
only if there are enough technology support and time for teachers 
to plan lessons and a school structure in which teachers may 
experiment with new technology the report concluded 
the center for technology in education operates under a 
fiveyear 49 million grant from the federal office of 
educational research and improvement 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
copies of the report can be obtained by sending a check for 5 
made out to bank street college of education to laura bryant bank 
street college of education 610 w 112th st new york ny 10025 
</TEXT>
