<TEXT>
leaders of the seven nations on the 
baltic sea have agreed to curb the pollution that has killed a 
third of life on the sea bed but the eastern europeans say theyll 
need western aid for the effort 
its a breakthrough for the ecological restoration of the 
baltic sea said swedish prime minister ingvar carlsson 
carlsson and prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki of poland hosted 
the twoday conference which ended monday with agreement that a 
comprehensive plan for cleaning up the baltic would be prepared by 
the end of next year 
greenpeace international said the conferences declaration was 
too vague the environmental organization has already criticized 
the baltic nations for aiming too low with their 1988 plan to halve 
emissions into the baltic by 1995 
sweden and denmark already have national cleanup strategies and 
the conference was seen as stepping up pressure on the soviet union 
and former east bloc countries to catch up 
eastern european delegates acknowledged that they have lagged in 
pollution control but made it clear they would need western money 
and expertise to help end environmentally damaging practices 
the policy of earmarking meager financing for conservation 
activities in the past is responsible for this state of affairs 
said vatsilu doguzhiev deputy chairman of the soviet council of 
ministers 
ecological problems require an enormous amount of effort and 
finance he said 
according to papers presented at the conference half of all 
nitrogen emissions into the baltic come from poland one of the 
most serious sources of pollution is the vistula river which flows 
into the sea 
several scientific studies have shown that the baltic is 
suffocating as phosphates and nitrates flood the sea encouraging 
the growth of algae that uses up the oxygen needed by plants and 
fish 
mazowiecki stressed the need for the cleanup but said his 
countrys involvement may be unrealistic without significant 
technological and financial support from abroad 
</TEXT>
