<TEXT>
egyptian soldiers are in saudi arabia 
prepared to fight if iraq invades but thats a thousand miles from 
cairo and life goes on as usual in the teeming metropolis of the 
middle east 
this is mango and guava season decorated carts haul stacks of 
the fruit into the city juice sellers costumed from the pages of 
the arabian nights are popular attractions 
hawkers clog crowded sidewalks with illegal tables holding 
mechanical toys and live tortoises for children hair bows for 
mothers there are evening carriage rides along the nile for those 
with the money to pay 
american and european teenagers summer vacations over have 
returned to their favorite haunts greasy burger pizza hut and 
roys goes mexican at the marriott hotel 
nightly television includes knots landing reruns johnny 
weissmuller swings across the screen in tarzan finds a son 
a recent days outing to the suez canal past dozens of egyptian 
military installations produced one unusual sight a taxi tooling 
down the road with a monkey on top the bases were quiet 
a canalside peanut vendor watched the us navy battleship 
wisconsin and french aircraft carrier clemenceau steam into the red 
sea heading for the persian gulf he barely glanced at the rest of 
the convoy 
ive seen enough ships he said but the helicopter escort 
was great 
in cairo coffeehouses there is far more talk of how to win 
peace than how to wage war 
we all are praying for peace a student said nobody wants 
war 
the tension engendered by iraqs occupation of kuwait on aug 2 
which caused 4000 egyptian soldiers and tens of thousands of 
americans to be sent to saudi arabia seems remote from most of 
cairos 12 million residents 
expatriate parents speak of frantic telephone calls from abroad 
urging caution 
an american grandfather demanded that his daughter bring his 
grandchildren home they are home she replied 
life in cairo surges onward with the same chaos and madness it 
has possessed through the millennium since the city was founded in 
969 
change comes so often and so swiftly to cairo that talk of a 
possible persian gulf war was diluted from the start by more 
immediate cares rising prices for gasoline and food shortages amd 
gigantic sales that brought more jostling people than usual to 
downtown cairo 
august was hot and steamy cairos air quality was lousy 
as always the welltodo including president hosni mubarak 
spent the month at the mediterranean seaside of egypts summer 
capital alexandria schools and universities will not open for 
several weeks 
except for the islamic holy month of ramadan when egyptians 
party all night and sleep until noon august is the only time cairo 
traffic takes a break 
this year however there appeared to be more fenderbenders 
than usual taxi drivers blamed an influx of drivers from the gulf 
kuwaitis cant drive in cairo one said after swerving to 
avoid a collision theyre not used to so many cars 
kuwaiti families stranded by iraqs annexation of their country 
are moving from hotels to apartments becoming part of the calliope 
that is cairo kuwaiti flags fly from some cars others are covered 
by photographs of kuwaits deposed emir sheik jaber alahmed 
alsabah 
tired egyptian workers returning from kuwait and iraq many now 
penniless head for their villages in jammed taxis they carry 
tattered suitcases instead of the household appliances and 
electronic goods they had always been able to bring as gifts 
extra security precautions in cairo are minimal 
since the invasion the government has kept four truckloads of 
helmeted riot police near the iraqi embassy in zamalek a nile 
river island opposite downtown cairo 
at first the trucks stood in relentless sunshine at the 
treeless front of the embassy but wearing riot gear in a covered 
truck is uncomfortable business and the vehicles were moved half a 
block to the protection of shade trees 
officers sit around square tables drinking tea and reading 
newspapers a single truck is parked outside the safir zamalek a 
nearby residential hotel owned by kuwaitis 
security trucks also sit near the embassies of kuwait and saudi 
arabia several miles away farther south along the nile less 
fortunate soldiers spend their hours in hot rickety trucks of 
faded blue halfway between cairo and the rich suburb of maadi 
where many diplomats and wealthy egyptians live 
outside the downtown offices of iraq airways where long lines 
of egyptian workers once waited two policemen lean against the 
polished white facade 
another pair yawn through their watch guarding kuwait airways 
offices in a suburban shopping arcade 
to old hands theres nothing new in all this 
in 1942 cairos cabarets and swinging night life gave no hint 
that the decisive battle of el alamein was raging 150 miles away 
