<TEXT>
drop the novel step away from the car youre 
under arrest for having an overdue library book 
starting on thursday your overdue books could land you in police 
custody a law signed by gov michael s dukakis in june would 
allow the arrest of library scofflaws if they have received notice 
that their books are 30 days overdue 
the law also raises the maximum fine for an overdue book from 
50 to 500 
although the law makes no mention of a jail sentence for an 
overdue book it allows for up to five years in prison and a fine 
of 25000 for the theft of library property worth more than 250 
gregor trinkausrandall a collection management consultant for 
the massachusetts board of library commissioners said librarians 
need tough enforcement tools 
any library book that is not returned therefore has to be 
replaced by the library and is money out of the towns pocket that 
could be spent on other materials he said 
the town of shrewsbury for example loses an estimated 12000 
a year in library materials trinkausrandall said books are not 
cheap he said im not even talking about rare books an art 
book can cost 100 or more 
david linsky a defense attorney in cambridge criticized the 
measure 
i think the police are having enough trouble chasing down 
murderers and rapists without having to keep up with people who 
have overdue library books he said 
trinkausrandall said he expects librarians will use discretion 
in sending police after those with overdue books 
most libraries will go through more notification of somebody 
giving them the benefit of the doubt he said in most of the 
cases they are not going to say on day 31 send the police out 
linsky complained that the law allows the arrest of library 
scofflaws without a warrant something that cant be done with an 
offense such as assault and battery he said the measure is 
absolutely 100 percent unenforceable 
if the police are told by an employee of the library that you 
have an overdue library book then the police can arrest you in any 
public place and put the handcuffs on you he said thats the 
real horror show of this thing 
steven crawford a spokesman for dukakis said the 
administration is taking another look at the law to determine 
whether the questions that are being raised are accurate 
massachusetts is not the first state to get tough on those who 
keep library books at home beyond the due date 
in georgia a woman was jailed overnight when she failed to 
appear in court to explain why her books were not returned the 
woman said she was sure she had returned the books and sued the 
county 500000 last year for being jailed 
in florida and south carolina police have also been put on 
notice to track down those with overdue books 
