<DOCNO> AP900904-0014 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
jupiters great red spot may soon lose some 
of its red because of a change in the weather on the largest planet 
in the solar system 
a 6200milewide belt of clouds on the planet is starting to 
change to its typical dark brown smoggy color 13 months after it 
turned white astronomers say when the belt turns brown its winds 
start feeding ammonia ice crystals into the great red spot washing 
out some of the color 
the great red spot is a hurricane almost twice the size of 
earth the cloud belt or southern equatorial belt sits just north 
of the great red spot 
several astronomers from nasas infrared telescope facility on 
hawaiis mauna kea volcano and from other observatories around the 
world reported the change to the international astronomical unions 
central bureau for astronomical telegrams an astronomy reporting 
agency in cambridge mass 
scientists study weather on other planets to understand rules 
governing weather on all planets including earth 
in july 1989 british astronomer gm hurst first noticed that 
the southern equatorial belt was changing from brown to white and 
growing colder 
but during the past two weeks astronomers observed the cloud 
belt starting to turn brown and get warmer according to telegrams 
sent by the central bureau on aug 22 and on wednesday 
the belt changes to white when jupiters internal heat pushes 
enough ammonia ice crystals upward in the atmosphere where winds 
over 300 mph spread the crystals out to form a white deck of 
lightreflecting cirrus clouds 
the cloud belt changes to brown when violent storms mix 
jupiters atmospheric gases allowing sunlight to trigger reactions 
by the ammonia and natural gas that creates brownish smog in the 
planets atmosphere 
when the cloud belt turns white the winds diminish reducing 
the amount of ice entering the great red spot and allowing it to 
turn darker red 
the cloud belt faded from brown to white in the early 1970s 
then turned brown again in 1974 remaining that way until 13 
months ago 
the great red spot faded to dim gray in 1976 but regained its 
brick red color after the southern equatorial belt turned white 
last year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
