<TEXT>
defenders of first amendment rights lament the 
retirement of supreme court justice william j brennan but say the 
views of his prospective replacement david h souter on freedom 
of speech and the press are somewhat encouraging 
no one could conclude he has an ax to grind against the media 
or against first amendment claims henry kaufman of the promedia 
libel defense resource center said of souter arguably we will 
get a fair hearing but hes no brennan 
brennan retired in july after a 34year career as the high 
courts leading voice of liberalism he wrote a 1964 landmark 
opinion giving the news media broad protection against libel suits 
by public figures and recently authored opinions barring criminal 
prosecution of those who burn the american flag in protest 
the senate judiciary committee is scheduled to begin hearings on 
souters nomination sept 13 most of what is known of his views 
have come from his writings as a new hampshire state judge 
president bush named souter to the 1st us circuit court of 
appeals in boston this year 
some who have studied the handful of opinions souter wrote on 
first amendment issues during his seven years on the new hampshire 
supreme court say they are heartened that bush didnt choose 
someone with apparent rigid ideas that could limit free expression 
i think hes been very balanced on freepress issues said 
claudia haskell of the first amendment congress hes in the 
mainstream 
however the advocates said they dont expect souter to be an 
ardent defender of free expression if he wins confirmation 
kaufman said souters opinions seem to reflect more interest 
in the complexity of the law than a passion for the 
underlying rights at issue 
souters decisions seem to reflect a cautious craftsman whose 
views are not expansive in protecting first amendment rights 
said floyd abrams a new york lawyer whose clients include the news 
media 
there are so many areas of the law in which someone would want 
to know judge souters philosophic views that i think in his case 
more than most the exploration of his general orientation may 
indeed tell more than could be learned from particular cases 
abrams said he added that his conclusions could change after 
souter testifies to the judiciary committee 
some commentators said they were encouraged that souter had 
expressed in cases unrelated to the first amendment strong 
support for supreme court precedent 
jane kirtley head of the reporters committee for freedom of the 
press said she was pleased that souter appears to have little 
inclination to topple key rulings 
lets face it weve got some good court decisions sitting up 
there right now she said i dont see anything that would 
suggest souter would be antimedia 
here is a summary of souters opinions in some first amendment 
cases as a state supreme court judge 
souter wrote for the court in 1985 when it reinstated a police 
officers libel suit against a newspaper that published a letter to 
the editor accusing the officer of misconduct 
souter said a jury is entitled to decide whether the letter made 
factual assertions or only expressed opinions shielded from libel 
attack 
the ruling in some respects seems to have foreshadowed a us 
supreme court decision this year that has the news media worried 
it said statements of opinion are not automatically immune to libel 
suits if arguably they contain factual assertions 
in 1984 souter wrote for the court in upholding a libel 
verdict against a newspaper that published an editorial about 
obscene and harassing telephone calls the newspaper was sued 
by a man mentioned in the editorial who was convicted of making 
harassing but not obscene calls 
while the newspaper had published a separate accurate account of 
the case souter said the publication was negligent in printing an 
editorial referring to obscene phone calls 
souter dissented from the courts 1988 opinion that permitted a 
libel suit against hustler magazine 
the court allowed an outofstate resident to take advantage of 
a new hampshire law that a publication may be sued for libel for up 
to six years after making a defamatory statement most states 
allowed only three years to sue 
souter said the ruling encouraged the evil practice of 
forumshopping and said the state had little interest in protecting 
the reputation of someone who never set foot in new hampshire 
prior to trial 
writing for the court last year souter barred a supporter of 
presidential candidate lyndon larouche from attaching a cardboard 
sign to a tree and lamppost outside city hall in manchester nh 
but souter said the man was free to pass out leaflets there without 
a permit 
while a trial judge in 1981 souter ruled in favor of two 
reporters for the university of new hampshire student newspaper who 
said they were trying to protect their confidential sources the 
judge barred a murder defendant from forcing the reporters to 
testify 
souter said the defendants claim that revealing the sources 
might point to other suspects in the murder was sheer 
speculation 
