<TEXT>
rail and barge movements of farm commodities 
into market channels have been fairly normal this year and should 
continue in good shape through this falls big harvest season an 
agriculture department report says 
the mideast crisis is driving up oil prices and analyst tq 
hutchinson of the departments economic research service said that 
probably will boost transportation costs in the coming months 
but because railroads often hold significant inventories of 
diesel fuel and obtain fuel under longterm contracts their costs 
are partly shielded from shortterm fluctuations in fuel prices 
he said 
rail rates have increased only slightly reflecting declining 
railroad operating costs over the past 12 months adjusted for 
productivity increases hutchinson said for the third quarter of 
1990 the interstate commerce commission has projected costs 
adjusted for productivity to be down 1 percent from the second 
quarter 
river barge operators will try to pass on higher fuel costs but 
competitive pressures may dampen attempts to raise rates 
writing in the september issue of agricultural outlook magazine 
hutchinson said the nations transportation services are expected 
to be adequate for the remainder of the year 
however projected low water flows from the missouri river 
mean that navigation will be difficult on the mississippi river 
between st louis and memphis this fall he said 
streamflow throughout the huge mississippi and missouri 
watersheds plummeted last year in the aftermath of the 1988 drought 
and its lingering effects in the northern great plains 
the army corps of engineers has announced that the missouri 
river will be closed for navigation beginning nov 1 the same as 
last year 
that will boost the cost of grain marketing for companies that 
usually depend on missouri but it will not markedly cramp the 
distribution systems ability to handle demand hutchinson said 
looking at operations earlier this year hutchinson said the 
mississippi river system returned to its dominant role in 
transporting feed grains for export 
in the first six months of 1990 he said corn accounted for 77 
percent of the downstream traffic on the mississippi and soybeans 
13 percent may shipments were a 10year high for the month 
mississippi water levels were high in the spring with march 
readings at st louis averaging 138 percent above a year earlier 
and 13 percent above the months 44year average 
by july there was a substantial lowering to 186 feet although 
the longterm average at st louis for july is only 134 feet 
hutchinson said the july 1989 average reading was 17 feet 
water levels are expected to fall for the remainder of the 
year the analyst wrote even so towboat captains have become 
experienced with low water conditions and the new melvin price 
lock and dam complex near alton ill is expected to greatly 
reduce the number and length of backups that characterized the past 
two seasons 
