percent of the total water flow at st louis came from the missouri 
river and between 40 percent and 60 percent of the flow came from 
the missouri river reservoir system in montana and the dakotas 
the figures for 1989 are not yet available he said but the 
percentages are believed to be about the same as for 1988 
normally runoff chiefly from snowmelt would add 25 million 
acrefeet of water to the reservoirs each year hutchinson said 
but from 1987 to 1989 only 125 million to 213 million were 
added annually 
the forecast for 1990 was 205 million acrefeet of runoff for 
the reservoirs but hutchinson said the actual runoff apparently 
will be somewhat less than that 
the corps of engineers estimates that it will take six years 
of normal runoff to raise the missouri river reservoirs to full 
capacity he said 
in june heavy rains raised the missouris level at kansas city 
to nearly 20 feet up 300 percent from a year earlier but at sioux 
city iowa levels in june averaged 166 feet down about one foot 
from june 1989 
hutchinson said the corps of engineers decided to terminate the 
navigation season on nov 1 and reduce the flow of water to about 
82 percent of normal suggesting that water levels will plummet in 
november 
last november the rivers level at sioux city averaged 10 feet 
at the flood gauge a sixfoot drop from october he said it seems 
probable that the flow from the missouri into the mississippi this 
year will be no more and probably less than in 1989 
thus navigation conditions on the mississippi between st 
louis and cairo ill should remain adequate through the summer 
but could deteriorate early in the fall hutchinson said low 
water might be encountered well before the winter freeze 
