less than two months before 
national elections prime minister geoffrey palmer resigned today 
after polls indicated the governing labor party would be routed 
with him at its helm 
labor chose external relations and trade minister mike moore to 
head the government and tackle the daunting task of turning around 
the party before the oct 27 balloting palmer took office 13 
months ago after defeating moore in a party vote to replace david 
lange as prime minister 
the latest polls show the opposition national party with a 
2to1 or more lead over labor although many voters say they have 
not made up their minds 
under labor leadership since 1984 new zealand has undergone a 
wideranging economic transformation with many stateowned 
businesses being sold off 
but the electorate is unhappy with the ailing economy inflation 
is at 76 percent shortterm interest rates at nearly 15 percent 
and unemployment has reached 73 percent 
moore 41 who in recent months repeatedly denied he would seek 
to unseat palmer told a news conference that new zealanders wanted 
a new direction and that his bid for the leadership in no way 
is a reflection on mr palmers service to new zealand 
