<TEXT>
the governing party which has run mexico for 
60 years has pledged polticial reforms ranging from recognition of 
churches to citizen participation in the selection of party 
candidates 
we have achieved a new democracy institutional 
revolutionary party president luis donaldo colosio said at a 
closing speech monday before 9000 delegates to the partys 
threeday 14th national assembly 
the party known as pri has dominated mexican politics since it 
was founded in 1929 its presidential candidates have traditionally 
been chosen by their predecessors and only in the past two 
elections has there been any public discussion on the matter 
the government has also refused to legally recognize churches 
which may not own land clergymnen may not vote still 
anticlerical laws are widely ignored in this intensely catholic 
country and the government has twice played host to pope john paul 
ii 
in one resolution the party called for separation of 
religious and political affairs and equal treatment of all 
public manifestations of religion 
but the most important reforms adopted by the assembly dealt 
with change in the selection of candidates at all levels giving 
control over the process to local party organizations the reforms 
did not however spell out how citizens would participate in 
candidate selection 
the democratic reforms had strong backing from president carlos 
salinas de gortari who has described such political changes as an 
essential part of his program to modernize the mexican economy and 
political system 
colosio told delegates that the party must adapt to a changing 
mexican society and confront the threat of electoral losses 
from now on any militant that wants to be a candidate will 
have to face first the judgement of his fellow citizens colosio 
told delegates 
in 1988 salinas won with just over 50 percent of the vote the 
smallest margin in party history and the party suffered its first 
senate losses leftist parties gained ground in the central part of 
the country defeating salinas in the federal district and a few 
states 
in 1989 the party lost its first governors race conceding 
victory to the conservative national action party in baja 
california 
the party is preparing for crucial city elections in the state 
of mexico which includes most of the mexico city suburbs it is 
also readying itself for 1991 midterm congressional elections 
in another resolution membership in the allpowerful central 
committee was cut from 37 to nine and the influence of party 
peasant and labor organizations in the committee was reduced 
the pri also appealed to private businessmen to join in the 
countrys efforts at modernization 
the mexican entrepreneur the party said must be 
innovative take chances and work together with other sectors of 
society 
another reform that brought applause from delegates was a 
recommendation that political trials be instituted for corrupt 
government officials 
outgoing government officials with reputations for corruption 
have traditionally been exempted from legal action in the last two 
administrations however several officials have been jailed the 
highest of them being the director of the government oil monopoly 
salinas told the delegates he was proud to be a member of the 
new party 
the reforms are not to satisfy our enemies but to create a 
better society salinas said their purpose is to maintain the 
mexican revolution in power they are changes to win votes 
democratically they are changes for victory not to give away 
power 
