<TEXT>
pope john paul ii today urged africas 
roman catholics to abandon the unspeakable crime of witchcraft 
a practice that threatens the churchs foundations on the continent 
in his homily at an outdoor mass on the shores of lake victoria 
the pope also spoke out against abortion saying the dignity of 
every human person from the moment of conception until natural 
death must be respected 
his sermon came on the fourth day of his seventh visit to 
africa a vast continent with a declining economy and a soaring 
birth rate that is expected to double its population of 500 million 
within 20 years 
tanzanias average per capita annual income is only about 200 
making it one of the worlds poorest countries few of subsaharan 
africas 48 other nations fare much better 
the pope also condemned artificial birth control calling it 
contrary to the truth of married love by which husband and wife 
become cooperators with god in giving life 
concerned about their birth rates and their lack of resources to 
adequately care for swelling populations tanzania and many other 
african nations actively support birth control programs 
john paul said respect for human dignity also is threatened in 
africa by the practice of uchawi or witchcraft he said it leads 
practioners into forms of enslavement and false worship 
he also criticized the traditional african custom of mahari or 
a dowry payment by a husband to the family of his bride in the 
past these payments usually took the form of cattle sheep and 
goats increasingly they involve substantial cash payments 
the pope said there are many authentic and praiseworthy human 
values associated with the dowry tradition but he asked do 
not excesses and abuses of these customs lead to attitudes which 
judge the dignity and worth of persons only on the basis of wealth 
and possessions 
the roman catholic church in africa only a century old faces 
the problem of incorporating traditional practices in the liturgy 
without overwhelming the faiths traditions and beliefs 
the church has gone a long way in recent years in the process of 
africanization adopting the use of tribal drums native dance 
music and language in the liturgy 
the pope has encouraged the process while warning that the basic 
tenents of catholic faith and teaching cannot be compromised he 
has stressed the churchs laws on polygamy superstition and 
priestly celebacy on his current visit 
an estimated 50000 faithful attended the mass on a hillside 
above mwanza a relatively prosperous cottongrowing and 
goldmining center on the southern shores of the worlds third 
largest lake 
nineteen married couples repeated their marriage vows before the 
pope he also gave first communion to a group of children dressed 
in white finery 
as he neared the halfway point of his 10day trip the pope 
ended the day in moshi a farming and resort city on the southern 
slopes of snowcapped mount kilimanjaro at 18864 feet the tallest 
mountain in africa 
his pilgrimage will take him to tiny burundi on wednesday then 
on to neighboring and equally small rwanda 
he ends his visit on sept 10 in the west african nation of 
ivory coast where he will consecrate a massive 133 million 
basilica 
</TEXT>
