twothirds vote among league members 
klibis resignation highlights divisions within the arab league 
over the gulf crisis as well as the groups decision to move the 
league headquarters from tunis back to cairo its original seat 
klibi had been the arab leagues secretary general since 1979 
when the organization moved to tunis he was reappointed to the 
post in march for another fiveyear term 
the league has been openly divided since its aug 10 arab summit 
in cairo over the persian gulf crisis which was precipitated by 
iraqs aug 2 seizure of kuwait 
the summit condemned iraq and agreed to send a token arab force 
to bolster american troops defending saudi arabia from any move by 
iraq to seize more territory 
tunisia boycotted the summit provoking anger from egypt and 
saudi arabia the most vocal arab nations in their opposition to 
the iraqi invasion 
while more than half the league members took what was viewed as 
a prowestern stance others sided in varying degrees with iraq 
it was klibis job to reconcile the two camps but at a meeting 
of arab league foreign ministers last week saudi minister prince 
saud alfaisal was sharply critical of the secretarygeneral 
in addition klibi has been caught in a battle over the location 
of the leagues headquarters which was moved to tunis after egypt 
declared peace with israel in 1979 and was barred from the league 
the decision to move the headquarters back to the egyptian 
capital has provoked protests from iraq iraqi foreign minister 
tariq aziz criticized the move because of what he called egypts 
partial attitude against iraq 
some have charged that klibi himself has resisted the move to 
cairo 
a meeting of arab league ministers has been called for sept 10 
in cairo where the transfer of the leagues headquarters back to 
cairo will be officially announced 
