weakness the department has said construction employment has 
declined for five straight months including the loss of 50000 
jobs in july after seasonal adjustment payrolls have fallen by 
100000 since last fall 
residential spending in july fell 04 percent to 1905 
billion its fourth consecutive drop including a 34 percent loss 
in june 
singlefamily spending was down 13 percent to 1102 billion 
for its fourth straight decline including a 16 percent drop in 
june apartment construction fell 16 percent to 184 billion 
after a 36 percent drop in june it has fallen for three months 
the new structure component will continue to move down 
certainly through the end of the year seiders said adding that 
the report implies strong performance only in additions and 
alterations to existing structures 
this is what we usually see in down cycles he said 
people just add on to houses 
nonresidential spending rose 25 percent to 1075 billion 
after a 18 percent gain the previous month 
the only truly bright spot is the industrial component 
which was up 93 percent in july seiders said but the permit 
information has been weakening and we expect this part of the 
market will lose its momentum 
the other two major nonresidential components office 
buildings and other commercial construction such as shopping 
centers remains weak seiders said 
government spending edged down 02 percent to 1086 billion 
after rising 07 percent the previous month 
overall construction spending in july was 31 percent above that 
of july 1989 when it totaled 4290 billion 
