<TEXT>
the national institutes of health announced 
today that scientists have isolated the gene responsible for 
osteoarthritis a painful crippling disease that affects about 16 
million americans 
dr darwin j prockop of philadelphias thomas jefferson 
university and dr roland w moskowitz of case western reserve 
university in cleveland led the scientists who isolated a flawed 
gene that normally helps make collagen a protein that strengthens 
joints 
the scientists studied genetic material from 19 members of a 
threegeneration family and found that the faulty gene was 
affecting the family members as young as 16 
osteoarthritis leads to a wearing away of joints and serious 
cases of severe crippling it can affect the hands feet hips and 
knees 
identifying the gene officials said may lead to new treatments 
and even prevention 
understanding genetic mechanisms underlying osteoarthritis may 
give us the potential to intervene early in a painful disabling 
disease said dr james o mason assistant secretary of health 
</TEXT>
