businesses should play a greater role in 
improving schools by investing more dollars and personnel to boost 
quality and prepare students for the workforce a nationwide poll 
said tuesday 
the roper organization poll commissioned by an affiliate of the 
us chamber of commerce found 96 percent of americans with 
children in public school as well as 91 percent of all americans 
are concerned about the quality of education in their communities 
threequarters of those polled agreed that public schools are 
failing to prepare students for jobs now available sixtythree 
percent said most students will lack skills for jobs in the future 
most of the 1003 adult americans polled over the telephone last 
month were receptive to the involvement of business in local public 
education ninetyone percent said it is a good idea for business 
to provide equipment to schools while 6 percent thought it was a 
bad idea and 2 percent didnt know 
eightyfive percent want business to pay the cost of putting in 
a course to teach certain technical skills while 12 percent were 
against the idea and 3 percent didnt know eighty percent said 
business should give employees time off to teach a course in the 
school system compared with 15 percent against and 4 percent 
undecided 
seventytwo percent called on business to take the lead in 
improving community schools and 65 percent wanted business leaders 
to run for school boards 
it is interesting to note that the american public considers 
the business community the education safety net for the nation 
