the number of consumers 30 days or more behind 
on their bank loan payments increased in the apriljune period 
after falling the previous two quarters a trade group said tuesday 
the american bankers association said a survey of 800 banks 
showed a delinquency rate on consumer loans of 255 percent up 
from the 246 percent in the first quarter and far above the 230 
percent rate of a year ago 
the groups chief economist robert h dugger said that credit 
delinquencies are indicative of whats happening in the rest of 
the economy 
the current delinquency rate even though up somewhat is 
still considered moderate consumers have been slowing their 
spending for several quarters and are expected to remain 
cautious he said 
the delinquency rate includes seven types of closedend consumer 
loans personal two types of auto loans mobile home recreational 
vehicle property improvement and home equity 
the district of columbia reported the lowest delinquency rate 
with 122 percent followed by arizona with 124 percent and then 
nebraska with 138 percent 
the states with the worst rates were new hampshire with 599 
percent massachusetts with 503 percent puerto rico with 485 
percent and connecticut with 481 percent 
the delinquency rate for openended home equity credit lines 
which are tracked separately was virtually unchanged at 075 
percent compared with 079 percent in the first quarter 
