<TEXT>
austria said tuesday it was reimposing a 
visa requirement for poles and sending troops to the hungarian 
border to help stem an influx of east european refugees 
the interior ministry said polish citizens would once again need 
visas to travel to austria the visa requirement takes effect on 
friday and will be in force for six months 
the polish foreign ministry issued a brief statement expressing 
regret and surprise over austrias decision in retaliation 
the foreign ministry announced it was introducing a visa 
requirement for austrians for the same period 
austria has not required visas from poles since 1988 it was the 
only visafree travel destination in western europe for poles 
besides west berlin which will also change its regulations 
following the oct 3 german unification 
austria now finds itself facing a growing influx of east 
europeans over the past few months particularly poles and 
romanians who endure severe economic hardships at home 
austria says that with the exception of some romanians most of 
the new arrivals do not qualify for refugee status because they no 
longer face political persecution at home 
the main traiskirchen refugee camp south of vienna is currently 
accomodating 2000 people double its capacity the transfer of 
refugees to other facilities is slow 
in an effort to prevent romanians and other east europeans from 
illegally crossing the hungarianaustrian border austria said it 
would send 1500 soldiers in the next two days to the border region 
to assist customs officials 
chancellor franz vranitzky said the troops would be deployed for 
an initial period of 10 weeks 
interior minister franz loeschnak said monday the soldiers would 
be limited to patrolling the border and would only use their 
weapons in selfdefense 
the government said that if necessary soldiers may also be 
dispatched to patrol the borders with other eastern european 
countries austria is also bordered by czechoslovakia and 
yugoslavia 
in its statement the polish foreign ministry admitted some 
poles have engaged in illegal trade or work in austria but 
stressed that such phenomena cannot be a basis for making a 
decision limiting the freedom of travel of all citizens of both 
countries 
polish foreign minister krzysztof skubiszewski also criticized 
the austrian decision 
it is discrepant with our policy aiming at introducing a full 
freedom of movement of people in europe skubiszewski said in an 
interview for an evening radio newscast 
austrian authorities had threatened to restore the visa 
requirement for poles earlier this year in an effort to meet 
austrian concerns poland imposed strict customs controls and 
invited austrian customs officials to join their counterparts at 
polish border crossings 
foreign ministry spokesman wladyslaw klaczynski noted that more 
and more western countries were lifting visa requirements for 
hungarians and czechoslovakians but he said no western country was 
currently planning to do the same for poles 
klaczynski said the austrian decision amounted to a kind of 
discrimination against poles 
we do not deny that it has its cause but this cause does not 
justify such a decision we should aim at removing barriers not at 
erecting them he told the associated press 
 
