<TEXT>
two new studies of obesity and high blood 
pressure among children produced advice that sounds a lot like the 
admonitions of a strict parent watch what you eat and quit 
watching so much tv 
doctors studying a group of poor children in new york concluded 
that the childrens blood pressure depended in part on how much 
they weighed and exercised bad childhood habits could carry over 
to cause high blood pressure or heart disease when the children 
grow up the researchers warned 
there is evidence cardiovascular disease originates during 
childhood said the new york study which is published in 
wednesdays journal of the american medical association 
a second study a review of national data by the harvard school 
of public health and tufts new england medical center found that 
the more television obese children and adolescents watch the less 
likely they are to lose weight 
diet exercise and restriction of television viewing and other 
sedentary activities all appear necessary to halt the fattening of 
america said that report which was published in wednesdays 
edition of the journal of the american dietetic association 
the new york study was the first to examine the separate and 
combined effects of fitness and fatness in young innercity 
children said bernard gutin and his colleagues at columbia 
university 
over the last five years the researchers studied 216 children 
ages 5 and 6 recruited from clinics daycare centers and a 
hospital the children 91 percent of whom where hispanic came 
from poor families 
researchers took the childrens blood pressure tested their 
aerobic fitness on a treadmill and assessed their obesity by 
measuring their bodies and skin folds the report said it 
concluded that much of the difference in their blood pressures 
related to how fat and how fit they were 
while previous studies have shown that obesity and lack of 
fitness contribute to cardiovascular problems in adults it has 
never been shown before in children this young said gutin 
professor of applied physiology and education at columbia 
universitys teachers college 
we think of blood pressure as something we worry about as 
adults but it seems we have to worry about it when children are 
young he said in a telephone interview tuesday children are 
probably suffering damage to their coronary arteries even now 
the harvard study on television viewing grew from a second 
review of national data collected between 1963 and 1980 that data 
showed obesity increased by 46 percent among children and 
adolescents through the years though calorie intake hadnt risen 
proportionally said dietician lilian wy cheung 
she and other researchers went over the data again focusing on 
1900 children living throughout the united states said cheung 
director of the harvard nutrition and fitness project 
the chance of becoming fat increased 13 percent for each 
additional hour of television viewing daily the report said 
and the chances a youngster could be cured of obesity 
decreased 63 percent with each additional hour of television 
viewing daily the report said it defined cured as reducing weight 
to a desired level and keeping it off for five years 
previous studies have shown that watching television promotes 
obesity partly because it takes people away from more active 
pursuits also television commercials encourage people to eat 
highcalorie foods the study said 
