a new york company has agreed to pay 66 million 
toward cleaning up new bedford harbor where industrial pollution 
has forced closing of lobster and fishing grounds the federal 
government announced tuesday 
officials said the payment part of a settlement between the 
government and avx corp of new york city is one of the largest 
such payments in the history of the superfund the decadeold fund 
was set up to attack the nations worst cases of hazardous waste 
pollution 
avx was one of five companies accused in a federal complaint 
filed in 1983 of contributing to the pollution of new bedford 
harbor by releasing pcbs or polychlorinated biphenyls from 
manufacturing plants near the harbor pcbs have been found to cause 
cancer and their use has been restricted 
a call to avx headquarters for comment tuesday evening rang 
unanswered 
the complaint alleged that the pcbs damaged the harbors natural 
resources including 18000 acres of beaches fishing and 
lobstering grounds 
part of the 66 million settlement will reimburse the government 
for money it has already spent at new bedford home to one of the 
nations biggest commercial fishin fleets 
settlements such as this are the backbone of the superfund 
program said us environmental protection agency administrator 
william reilly in a news release epa is committed to an 
aggressive policy of making those who pollute pay for the cleanup 
we will continue to use every enforcement mechanism available to 
bring about more settlements and more private party cleanups 
the money is to be paid to the epa the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration and the state 
from 1947 through 1973 avx owned and operated what is now known 
as the aerovox plant avx recently merged with a japanese firm epa 
spokesman jim sebastian said tuesday 
studies by the environmental protection agency in the 1970s 
revealed high levels of pcbs in fish and shellfish in new bedford 
harbor as a result officials closed a 10squaremile area of the 
harbor to lobstering and closed a smaller area to fishing for 
bottomfeeding species they remain closed 
the government has reached an agreement in principle with two 
other companies named in the original complaints aerovox inc of 
new bedford and belleville industries inc a dissolved company 
officials said the terms of the settlement are to be presented in 
federal district court this fall 
a trial date of march 4 1991 has been set for the two other 
companies named in the complaint federal pacific electric co of 
delaware and cornelldubilier electronics inc of new bedford 
new bedford harbor is an urban tidal estuary at the head of 
buzzards bay 50 miles southeast of boston 
 
