<TEXT>
the savings and loan crisis has been in the 
headlines for several years now but for most americans it has 
amounted to a troubling but distant scandal recently more and 
more people are feeling the effects as the fallout trickles down to 
main street this first of a threepart series sampls on main 
street examines how the mess is taking its toll across the 
country on onceunlikely targets 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jean shoults was careful to pick a 
stable neighborhood with solid home values when she moved her 
family here two years ago but a single government decision may 
cost her 25000 in home equity 
you think youre buying the american dream and it turns into a 
nightmare mrs shoults said we are savings and loan victims 
shes not alone across the country more and more people are 
finding they too are sampl victims small businesses cant find 
loans subcontractors get stiffed on payments real estate markets 
are in ruins neighborhoods tied up in government red tape home 
buyers like judy and dave crenshaw in colorado springs colo 
battle through three mortgage companies and lose out on one home 
before finally getting a deal approved 
you wouldnt expect a small phoenix gold and jewelry store to be 
affected by the sampl debacle or a small advertising agency to end 
up a victim 
but the sampl mess has forced its way onto main street it has 
eliminated jobs crushed real estate values and weakened an already 
weak economy by crimping lending 
all this before the tax bite estimated at about 20 per family 
each month over the next 30 years 
its catching up to us quickly said david wyss chief 
financial economist at drimcgraw hill people are beginning to 
see more and more that were all victims 
for years the crisis had little impact for millions of 
americans because federal deposit insurance protected their 
accounts at savings banks shielding main street from the 500 
billion fiasco 
now however changes made by congress and regulators along 
with the restructuring of the industry are affecting the economy 
contributing to the nations credit crunch and possibly helping 
push a sluggish us economy closer to recession economists say 
the construction industry which is struggling nationwide is 
particularly hardhit by problems associated with sampls which 
traditionally have been the chief source of financing for home 
building 
demand is down but changes ordered by regulators also have 
helped curb building loans and analysts say banks and sampls are 
reluctant to make any real estate loan that might be labeled risky 
by regulators 
builders live on credit said dean crist research economist 
for the national association of home builders so what this has 
done is cut them off completely 
that sets off a chain reaction that ends on main street 
home buyers say theyve had a tough time finding financing and 
sellers have been battered by the lack of buyers the huge amount 
of empty real estate has depressed prices 
spring valley construction found itself an inadvertent victim of 
the sampl mess the company built much of stonebridge ranch a giant 
samplfinanced development north of dallas when the sampl went bust 
spring valley still was owed several hundred thousand dollars for 
work it already had done 
we dont get paid so our subcontractors dont get paid it 
ends up with the guy that works for a living jim duffy 
stonebridges vice president of operations 
the sampl crisis is impacting main street in many other ways 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
