<TEXT>
many foreign newspapers and magazines will need 
official permits to circulate in singapore under an amendment to 
the press law passed by parliament on aug 30 
in tightening controls on overseas publications the government 
served notice that it is a privilege and not a right for foreign 
newspapers to circulate in singapore said mah bow tan a 
minister of state 
they do so as foreign observers of the local scene and should 
not interfere in the domestic politics of singapore mah said 
the amendment to the newspaper and printing presses act applies 
to publications circulating more than 300 copies at intervals of 
one week or less with articles pertaining to the politics and 
current affairs of any country in southeast asia 
it is not aimed at a specific publication and not intended to 
prevent the free flow of information mah told parliament 
until now publications printed outside singapore did not need 
distribution permits unlike local newspapers and magazines 
a permit valid for one year and renewable may be refused or 
revoked without explanation under the amended law it will specify 
the number of copies to be sold and require the appointment of a 
local agent to accept any legal notices 
the amended law also calls for a security deposit to be posted 
against any court costs or other legal liabilities incurred by the 
publication 
the bill was introduced on july 18 and becomes law after it is 
signed by president wee kim wee it followed an announcement in 
april by deputy prime minister goh chok tong that the government 
was planning to make regional publications subject to the countrys 
jurisdiction 
goh commented after the government reported difficulties in 
serving notices on the asian wall street journal over a recent 
contempt of court action and a defamation suit 
</TEXT>
