<TEXT>
singer josephine baker was black danced 
naked and reveled in her sexuality from the 1920s until she died 
15 years ago most americans shunned her 
yet europeans loved the performer and her skin color and found 
little risque in her blatant exposure of it when baker was 
penniless toward the end of her life princess grace of monaco 
cared for her 
suddenly eight decades after her birth she now is the focus of 
three american films but it hardly denotes a surge in social 
consciousness the story of these movies is mostly about money 
bigname stars and rushing to capitalize on a very marketable story 
and how that process escalates once someone makes the first move 
home box office has the only completed version the josephine 
baker story will debut on the pay cable channel in february 1991 
the hbo version starring relative unknown lynn whitfield cost 8 
million and is the most expensive movie ever made by the 
18yearold network 
