this century few today know the enormity or impact of her life 
abroad 
her infamous banana dance in which she appeared naked save for 
a belt of fake bananas became the trademark of european revues 
she did more however than sing and dance in the nude 
baker was a tireless advocate of civil rights in world war ii 
she was a spy for the french resistance carrying intelligence 
information about german troop concentrations scrawled in invisible 
ink on her sheet music 
it was a long way from st louis where as a child she lived in 
an abandoned railroad car 
as a young woman in the early 1920s baker wanted to be famous 
americans wanted her to scrub their floors she fled to paris 
where color was less a discriminatory factor 
at the height of her paris glory she returned to new york and 
appeared in the 1936 ziegfeld follies with fanny brice and bob 
hope but the american public still was not ready for baker 
critics panned her in racist reviews 
humiliated she returned to europe in the 1950s her body 
ravaged by numerous surgeries that left her sterile she adopted 12 
children from around the world calling them her rainbow tribe 
tragedy illness and several marriages took their toll once the 
richest black person in the world baker was destitute shortly 
before her death 
she died in her sleep on the second night of a phenomenally 
successful comeback show in paris 
its a classic story said robert cooper senior vice 
president of hbo pictures the first thing i asked was if this 
is true why hasnt it been told 
the reason 
i think people just didnt know how to do it he said 
why now 
once one person decides to do it it forces everyone else to 
finalize their plans cooper said i think he who comes out 
first has a big advantage 
