<TEXT>
the venerable yiddish newspaper forward tutor 
and friend to generations of immigrants is taking a giant step out 
of the lower east side with a national englishlanguage weekly 
faced with diminishing readership of its yiddish edition the 
93yearold forward is braving a depressed newspaper market and 
ignoring widespread opinion that there is no need for a national 
jewish newspaper 
its owners are confident theyve located a niche among their 
competition and believe their publishing legacy will give them the 
powerful boost needed to succeed 
yiddish readers are very loyal and have an emotional tie with 
the paper historically said harold ostroff cochairman of 
forward publishing co they feel its a part of the family in a 
sense 
the forward traces its heritage back to 1897 when it emerged 
from the socialist labor movement to take up the cudgel of the 
yiddishspeaking working class 
the paper initially a daily served as teacher political 
advocate spiritual guide and psychiatrist for its readers mostly 
jewish immigrants to the united states it published everything 
from a famous advice column a bintel brief a bundle of 
letters to the writings of isaac bashevis singer during the 
early part of the century its readers numbered more than 250000 
but as the immigrants were assimilated into american society the 
number of yiddish speakers declined and so did the newspapers 
circulation 
the paper went weekly in 1983 and began to publish an 
englishlanguage supplement its circulation is now about 17000 
recognizing the need to shore up its readership and attract 
descendants of readers past the publishers have expanded the 
englishlanguage insert into a paper in its own right 
the first few issues of the paper which was first published may 
25 were distributed in the new york area only national 
circulation will begin friday with a projected circulation of 
30000 
like the yiddish forward the new paper combines news with 
social and cultural commentary about 40 percent of the paper will 
be hard news and analysis 40 percent cultural coverage and 
fiction and 20 percent editorial pages said seth lipsky editor 
of the forward and president of forward publishing co 
but lipsky said he realizes that reputation alone will not carry 
the fledgling paper 
the yiddish paper already has a deficit so the papers will 
share material along with circulation and advertising programs in 
some markets to ease costs 
the forward is entering a specialized market in which more than 
100 jewish publications are jostling for position the toughest 
challenge among them will come from the regional jewish presses 
new york city where lipsky expects half of his circulation has 
three established weeklies 
lipsky though believes there is room for his publication in 
each of the nations major cities his niche he said is in 
providing international and national jewish news coverage beyond 
what the larger metropolitan dailies and regional jewish papers 
offer 
his paper already has opened bureaus in jerusalem moscow 
paris washington and new york and will supplement the offices 
with stringers freelancers and news wire services there are plans 
to open bureaus in other cities including miami chicago and los 
angeles 
lipsky believes there are enough major jewish stories now to 
launch a paper he cites the rise of a antisemitic movement in the 
soviet union the prevailing conflict in israel and the 
democratization of eastern europe 
but jewish editors around the country and observers of the 
jewish press are less certain it will find a market 
i have a philosophy that our readership is much more 
interested in the news of the local jewish community than in news 
of the international jewish community said marc klein editor 
and publisher of the northern california jewish bulletin which has 
a circulation of about 27000 
klein who also is president of the american jewish press 
association said 70 percent to 80 percent of his paper is devoted 
to local stories 
gary rosenblatt editor of the baltimore jewish times agrees 
in baltimore they want to know from whos getting married to 
whos having a bar mitzvah to more weightier issues said 
rosenblatt whose paper has a circulation of about 20000 
abraham h foxman national director of the antidefamation 
league and a selfdescribed news junkie believes the forwards 
association with the yiddish forward will at least draw attention 
to the new paper 
the name forward has history has meaning in anglojewish 
life he said 
the national paper wont survive on forwards readers he said 
but there is a nostalgic element jews feel sensitive to 
tradition and continuity and history that will help the forward 
initially 
</TEXT>
