<TEXT>
for millions of americans the onset of 
alzheimers disease opens a frustrating and sometimes fruitless 
search for longterm care and services a congressional agency 
reports 
congress office of technology assessment concludes that as 
americas population ages a nationwide system is urgently needed 
to link people with the debilitating disease with services they 
need and can afford 
the report confused minds burdened families finding help 
for people with alzheimers and other dementias estimates about 
18 million people in the united states have dementia so severe 
that others must care for them continually 
an additional 1 million to 5 million have mild or moderate 
dementia 
alzheimers and other forms of dementia progressively destroy 
memory and a persons ability to deal with and understand events 
and people to accomplish routine household chores or even to take 
care of oneself 
the report noted that many people eventually require total care 
24 hours a day for the rest of their lives 
and that poses a problem for the families who must care for them 
the congressional study quoted a wisconsin alzheimers task 
force as reporting 
alzheimers family members often tell distressing stories 
about not knowing where to go for help going from one service 
provider to another in a vain search for assistance and being 
misinformed about the availability of services or eligibility for 
programs 
families dont even know what to ask for and many go through a 
maze of blind alleys before help is obtained an adult day care 
provider told the maryland task force 
the congressional agency concluded that while the need to 
develop an effective system to link those suffering from 
alzheimers to the services they need may seem removed from the 
ravages of the disease itself it is far from an abstract concern 
calling existing services complex and fragmented the report 
said 
the need for such a system comes alive for people who try to 
find appropriate services for a relative or friend and 
confront the existing lack of accurate information about services 
and the often bewildering array of public and private agencies 
individuals funding sources eligibility criteria rules and 
regulations that constitute the service environment 
it said establishing such a system will be difficult because of 
the competing web of service providers 
but it said that without such a system many people simply will 
not get the care they need 
and families and others who already must bear the physical 
and emotional demands of caregiving will continue to experience 
the frustration of not being able to obtain accurate information 
and assistance in locating and arranging services it said 
the agency said any linking system should include education an 
information and referral network outreach efforts and case 
management and recommended it have these other characteristics 
be easily identifiable nationwide by using a common name or 
logo or telephone number 
be available throughout a patients illness 
be able to help care givers who live a distance from the 
patient 
make available full information about available services and 
sources of financing 
sen brock adams dwash chairman of the senate subcommittee 
on aging said the report underscores the heroic yet staggering 
burdens facing care givers 
he noted congress will consider adjustments in the older 
americans act next year and said that presents an opportunity to 
address the problem 
families shouldnt have to go begging for help in caring for 
loved ones with alzheimers disease said sen howard metzenbaum 
dohio chairman of the senate labor and human resources committee 
this report shows we must redouble our efforts to fill the gaps 
in our health care system 
