but as the countrys population of 39 million ages rapidly 
fewer and fewer elderly spaniards will be able to live with their 
children the traditional way of dealing with aging in most spanish 
families 
this is just one of the changes resulting from the acceleration 
of the graying of spanish society according to doctors and 
activists who work with the elderly 
they say more nursing homes will be needed the health care 
system will have to adapt and new programs will have to be 
developed to help the elderly live independently as long as they 
can 
according to official statistics 5 million spaniards are 65 or 
older up from 46 million four years ago that is projected to 
rise to 61 million by 2000 
as their numbers grow spanish senior citizens are beginning to 
unite to fight for their interests 
in 1988 they formed the council for the elderly banding 
together dozens of small groups with a combined membership of more 
than 1 million 
the rapid aging of spains population is partly due to medical 
advances that have extended lifeexpectancy around the world 
but it is also the result of two peculiarly spanish events the 
193639 civil war and the end of the dictatorship of gen francisco 
franco in 1975 
because an estimated 1 million people died in the war and its 
aftermath of reprisals the current generation of senior citizens 
is smaller than it would have been otherwise 
as the remaining members of the war generation die and as the 
members of the larger postwar generation become senior citizens 
the elderly population will continue growing 
in 1970 the death rate was 841 per 1000 people in 1986 the 
last year for which comprehensive statistics are available it had 
fallen to 804 
meanwhile the birthrate has been falling dramatically from 
1955 per 1000 residents in 1970 to 1137 per 1000 in 1986 
the roman catholic church wielded great influence during the 
franco years and couples were encouraged to have large families 
but since the restoration of democracy in 1977 the influence of 
the church has waned and families are having fewer children 
in the last 10 years spain has changed as much as a normal 
