<TEXT>
people over age 65 make up 13 percent of 
the american population yet they take 30 percent of all 
prescription medicines sold in this country 
one billion times each year americans 65 or older take 
overthecounter drugs while these medicines offer many benefits 
they carry some risks 
almost everyone has a favorite story about the number of pills 
potions or elixirs taken by an older relative or friend while most 
of these stories have a happy ending some do not when taking any 
medication caution and common sense are necessary 
some basic rules for safe use of medicine 
take exactly the amount your doctor prescribes and follow the 
dosage schedule as closely as possible contact your doctor or 
pharmacist immediately if you have unusual reactions to medications 
make sure to ask your doctor for the specific name of the 
medicine prescribed ask why the drug is necessary how long the 
drug will have to be taken and if there is a good generic 
substitute 
tell your doctor about all other medicines prescription and 
over the counter you are taking interactions between medications 
can cause serious complications 
keep a daily log it should include the name of the medicine 
the doctor who prescribed it and the schedule for taking it 
include a space to check off each dose 
be sure to tell your doctor about past problems such as 
rashes indigestion dizziness lack of appetite that occurred 
when you took other medicines 
be sure to ask your doctor about side effects the best way to 
store the medicine and any special rules for example should the 
medicine be taken with foods or beverages should you limit your 
activities while taking the medicine 
make sure the directions printed on the medicine container are 
clear ask the pharmicist to use easytoopen containers if 
childproof ones are hard to handle the pharmacist can use large 
type on the label to help people with vision problems 
do not share your medicines with friends or relatives do 
not save medicines for use at another time 
do not stop taking a medicine prescribed by your doctor 
suddenly even if the symptoms go away 
ask your doctor from time to time to review the medications 
you take new information about medicines and how they affect older 
people is coming to light daily 
for more information on the safe use of medications contact 
elderhealth university of maryland school of pharmacy 20 north 
pine st baltimore md 21201 3013283243 
the elderhealth program offers free publications such as you 
and your medicines choosing the right not wrong 
nonprescription medicine and aging and how it affects your 
response to medicine 
also the food and drug administration center for drug 
evaluation and research consumer and professional affairs 
hfd365 5000 fishers lane rockville md 20857 301295801 
will provide information on specific drugs and their side effects 
keep in mind that a chemical agent strong enough to cure an 
ailment is also strong enough to cause harm if not used wisely 
although people should never stop taking medecine without medical 
advice if a drug seems to be causing more harm then good dont be 
afraid to discuss the matter with your doctor she or he may be 
able to prescribe a different drug that will be just as effective 
</TEXT>
