<TEXT>
a gardener feeling jaded might get a 
lift with a different bean go french perhaps with filets and 
flageolets countless varieties exist of this ancient food plant of 
the aztecs and incas and breeders keep creating new ones 
next years catalogs for example will introduce a pole bean 
called kentucky blue winner of an all america selections 
award the new bean combines traits of two already superb pole 
beans kentucky wonder and blue lake something like 
crossing a mercedes with a cadillac the breeder was calvin 
lamborn an idaho horticulturist who won a previous award for a 
sugar snap pea 
in 40 years of gardening the most attractive bean ive met is a 
superslim frenchie called haricot vert ahreeco vair 
probably best known as filet bean this sweet and tender bean 
is as fussy as it is elegant if you dont pick it at the right 
moment when its shoelacethin and no seeds have formed the pod 
toughens and the flavor goes off a single day can make a 
difference 
a gourmet shell bean becoming popular in american gardens is the 
flageolet flahjohlay celebrated in french cuisine as an 
accompaniment to roast lamb ive grown this tiny bean and admired 
its taste and looks but it takes a lot of them to make a meal 
this year i grew soybeans for the first time of probably asian 
origin the soy was practically unknown in america until commodore 
matthew perry brought some back from japan in 1854 this shell bean 
contains highquality protein and also some fat but breeders 
still are working to improve its flavor in my garden a variety 
called butterbeans took 90 days to mature producing small 
fuzzy pods about 2 inches long which were tough to pry open 
inside were two to three seeds as green as peas they kept their 
nice color in cooking but i found the taste on the bland side 
the soy and another shell bean the fava known in europe since 
homeric times are the only beans of nonamerindian heritage 
unlike other beans the fava withstands frost sown in midmarch 
it matures in june the earliest bean in my southern new york 
garden the fava also known as broad bean and windsor bean is 
delicious raw its still a favorite of picnickers in rome where 
in ancient times it gave its name to a prominent family the 
fabii but some people get an anemia called favism by eating 
raw or partly cooked favas 
bean pods of various shades of green yellow and purple 
contain some vitamin c and a and their taste is a summer delight 
but its the seeds that pack the protein hence the importance of 
shell beans in the human diet theyre meat substitutes meals of 
beans and rice beans and corn or beans and pasta combing 
proteins and carbohydrates are classic fare lima beans have been 
found in inca digs dating to 7000 bc in north america the 
colonists saw indians growing corn and beans together using the 
cornstalks for the beans to climb on 
you dont need much savvy to grow beans just be sure the soil 
is thoroughly warm when you sow them or theyll rot climbing beans 
need supports of course tripods being the best to resist high 
wind 
in this day of the freezer a gardener can store fresh shell 
beans saving himself the labor of drying them the fresh ones 
taste better than the mealyprone dry ones i think and they cook 
much faster seeds keep excellently in the freezer unlike pods 
which emerge from the ice limp and practically tasteless 
a shell bean called limelight gave me an abundant harvest in 
early august of light green beans resembling baby limas in looks 
and flavor each easytoshell pod contained six or seven seeds 
pole lima beans yield the biggest seeds of all some as large 
as quarters and with a taste far superior to the dried ones 
their longmaturing time makes them unfeasible for the coldest 
parts of the country in my borderline area i push the season by 
starting them indoors in pots like tomatoes by late may when i 
put them in the ground theyre sturdy plants with favorable 
weather i begin harvesting these big limas late in august more 
than a month before frost 
a helpful practice in growing limas is to sow the seeds with the 
eye the tiny notch facing down this makes them germinate 
easier in crusty soil some growers even leave the top of the seed 
uncovered ive had fine results with a variety of pole lima called 
king of the garden but now im ready to diversify next time 
im planting highly recommended lima called christmas 
</TEXT>
