<TEXT>
the manufacturing sector of the economy slowed 
during august for the second straight month as production and new 
orders dropped according to a survey of purchasing executives 
across the country 
the national association of purchasing management which tracks 
the manufacturing economy through a monthly poll of its members 
said its overall index of business activity fell to 470 percent 
from 474 percent in july when the index registers below 50 
percent it indicates the economy is weakening 
the drop in the index was the second consecutive decline the 
index stood at 511 percent in june 
news of the purchasing managers report contributed to a decline 
in the stock market at 1130 am edt the dow jones industrial 
average was off 1659 at 259777 
the purchasing managers reported a drop in production the first 
in seven months and attributed the slowdown to a sharp drop in new 
orders in july 
twenty percent of the purchasing managers said production was up 
in august while 54 percent reported it was unchanged and 26 
percent said it was down that compared with 19 percent reporting 
higher production in july 58 percent reporting it was unchanged 
that month and 23 percent saying it had slowed 
meanwhile new orders dropped for the second straight month 
twentyone percent of the purchasing managers said new orders 
rose during august while 49 percent reported they were stable and 
30 percent reported they had declined in july 19 percent reported 
growth in new orders 53 percent reported they were the same and 28 
percent said they had declined 
export orders also dropped sixteen percent of the purchasing 
managers said new export orders were up while 74 percent said they 
were the same and 10 percent said they were down the previous 
month 24 percent said they were up 66 said they were the same and 
10 percent said they were down 
imports declined with 7 percent of the respondents reporting an 
increase in imports 81 percent reporting they were the same and 12 
percent reporting a decline in july 9 percent reported imports 
were up 78 percent said they were the same and 13 percent said 
they were lower 
prices for raw materials rose during august a reflection of 
higher energy prices resulting from the persian gulf crisis 
twentytwo percent of the purchasing managers said they were 
paying higher prices 68 percent said they were paying the same 
amount and 10 percent said prices were down that compared with 12 
percent reporting higher prices in july 77 reporting stable prices 
and 11 percent reporting lower prices 
employment fell for the 18th straight month during august and at 
a slightly faster rate than in july 
nine percent of the purchasing executives said employment was up 
at their companies 68 percent said it was the same and 23 percent 
said it was down in july 13 percent said employment was up 70 
percent said it was the same and 17 percent reported a decline 
supplier deliveries slowed in august a sign of some economic 
strength as it indicated companies had more orders than they could 
fill 
seven percent of the purchasing managers surveyed said supplier 
deliveries were slower 87 percent reported they were the same and 
6 percent said they were faster that compared with 6 percent who 
said they were slower in july 83 percent who said they were the 
same and 11 percent who said they were faster 
inventories continued to decline in august but at a slowing 
pace 
sixteen percent of the respondents said their inventories were 
larger 57 percent said they were stable and 27 percent said they 
declined in july 10 percent reported they were up 55 percent 
reported they were the same and 35 percent said they were down 
the national association of purchasing management is a research 
and education organization with more than 33000 members its 
monthly survey queries purchasing executives at more than 300 
industrial companies across the nation 
</TEXT>
