<TEXT>
the federal environmental protection 
agency on tuesday charged united technologies corp with failing to 
comply with federal laws on the management of hazardous waste at 
six production plants 
the epa said inspections of five pratt amp whitney aircraft 
manufacturing plants and one hamilton standard plant revealed more 
than 100 violations of the federal law that mandates 
cradletograve management of hazardous waste 
the alleged violations include improper handling of hazardous 
waste storage of hazardous waste without a permit inadequate 
record keeping inadequate training of personnel and inadequate 
monitoring of groundwater 
in addition the epa said utc violated the terms of a 1989 
consent agreement it had entered into with epa 
the suit filed in us district court in hartford seeks a 
court order forcing utc to comply with environmental laws and 
unspecified fines 
its the number of violations as opposed to the severity 
that were concerned with said us attorney stanley a twardy 
who filed the civil suit on behalf of the epa 
julie belaga the epas regional administrator in new england 
said utc faces fines and penalties in the millions of dollars 
between 1985 and 1989 the company paid 210000 in penalties to 
the epa 
she said the alleged violations do not pose any direct threat to 
human health and safety the facilities named in the suit are all 
in connecticut 
the violations at the utc facilities are serious and 
persistent she said at a news conference utc has not 
implemented corporate management systems that would ensure 
environmental compliance at all its facilities 
epa officials said the waste at issue in the utc case is 
byproducts from the production of jet engine parts 
peter kowalchuk a spokesman for utc said the company was 
reviewing the lawsuit and had no immediate comment 
utc based in hartford is a major government contractor that 
designs and makes pratt amp whitney jet engines otis elevators and 
escalators carrier air conditioning equipment sikorsky 
helicopters hamilton standard jet controls and norden systems 
radar systems for battlefield operations 
the company employs about 50000 people in connecticut and 
200000 worldwide 
