<DOCNO> AP900904-0231 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
memories magazine is cutting back its 
publication schedule because of the weak advertising climate its 
publishers announced tuesday 
diamandis communications inc a us subsidiary of frances 
hachette sa said that regular publication of memories will be 
suspended with its october issue it said memories will appear 
twice a year starting in 1991 
the magazine has been published every other month since early 
1989 and plans had been to make it a monthly this fall 
but peter diamandis president and chief executive of diamandis 
communications said the current softness in the advertising 
marketplace makes it imprudent to continue the current rollout 
plan 
hachette made the move after efforts to sell the magazine failed 
memories was launched in the spring of 1988 and sought to tap 
readers fascination in the past by taking another look at major 
events of the past 50 years among the stories it updated were the 
battle of britain the kennedy assassination the march of dimes 
crusade and baseball slugger ted williams 
but it ran into a tough ad environment ad pages in magazines 
were down 33 percent in the first half of 1990 compared with a 
year earlier according to publishers information bureau and no 
signs of a pickup in demand are evident 
so far this year the ad slump has figured in the closing 
suspension consolidation and redesign of several magazines 
woman 7 days and southpoint magazines have folded psychology 
today suspended publication in january but hopes to reappear in 
january manhattan inc magazine ceased publication and merged with 
the fashion magazine m under the new title m inc the nightlife 
magazine details was converted into a general interest mens 
magazine 
didier guerin president of hachette publications inc which 
oversees diamandis communications said memories was up for sale 
for a couple months and that a deal was nearly reached with 
mortimer zuckerman the real estate baron who is chairman and 
editor in chief of us news amp world report and chairman of the 
atlantic monthly magazine 
zuckerman said in a telephone interview that he talked with 
hachette about memories but said we never made a formal proposal 
to buy the magazine 
we came to the conclusion that the economy was so bad and 
getting worse that it wasnt good time to be excessively 
adventuresome he said 
guerin said the deteriorating economic climate is prompting 
advertisers to cut back on ad spending the last thing they need 
is a new publication that is not established he said 
nonetheless he said memories would be published twice a year 
because its still a good concept still a strong name and we 
should be able to keep it alive at that rate if the economy 
improves he said the magazine could be published more often it 
has promised advertisers a circulation of 600000 
the magazine had a staff of 27 and guerin said efforts would be 
made to find jobs for them at other hachette magazines those other 
titles include boating car and driver elle and popular 
photography 
guerin said there were a few others in addition to zuckerman 
who expressed interest in memories but he declined to identify 
them 
he said none of the other hachette magazines are on the market 
earlier this year hachette put its womans day magazine up for 
sale to trim the companys debt but pulled it off the market in 
july after bidders failed to show up with the price it wanted 
the magazines demise comes less than two weeks before the 
premiere of a weekly television show that has licensed the 
magazines name memories then and now 
the show is being produced by nbc news productions a unit of 
the national broadcasting co and will be carried starting sept 
15 on more than 120 stations serving more than 80 percent of the 
nations households with tv 
therese byrne head of the unit said there was no editorial 
link between the magazine and the television show however and 
that the reduced frequency of the magazine should have no impact on 
the show 
