<TEXT>
the nations purchasing managers said tuesday 
that manufacturing slowed in august providing more evidence of a 
looming recession and signs that the persian gulf crisis is taking 
a toll on the economy 
the national association of purchasing management which tracks 
the manufacturing economy through a monthly poll of its members 
said its overall index of business activity at 300 industrial 
companies fell to 470 percent from 474 percent in july 
when the index registers below 50 percent it indicates the 
economy is weakening 
the drop in the index was the second consecutive monthly 
decline the index stood at 511 percent in june 
the purchasing managers report contained few surprises but 
still was evidence that the economy is slowing down and slowing 
down fast said david wyss chief financial economist for 
drimcgraw hill in lexington mass 
the report said production and new orders were down in august 
prices for raw materials moved sharply higher and employment was 
down prices and employment appeared to be affected by the 
monthlong persian gulf crisis 
wyss said the employment component in particular suggests 
quite frankly that businesses are quite scared by the mideast 
they taking on fewer people 
economic news from washington tuesday also was less than 
encouraging the commerce department reported construction spending 
edged up 04 percent in july for its first gain in four months but 
the government revised downward its estimate of spending in may and 
june 
despite the july gain analysts expect the industry to remain 
weak due to consumer caution high interest rates tight lending 
requirements and in some areas overbuilding 
a report on productivity was equally downbeat the labor 
department said the productivity of american workers improved for 
the first time in more than a year climbing in the second quarter 
at an annual rate of 15 percent 
but the advance was well below the level needed to significantly 
boost americans standard of living furthermore the productivity 
report contained figures showing steep labor cost increases which 
elevated concerns that inflation is accelerating especially in 
light of the middle east oil crisis that threatens to step up price 
increases 
the purchasing managers noting production was off for the first 
time in seven months attributed the slowdown to a sharp drop in 
new orders in july 
twenty percent of the purchasing managers said production was up 
in august while 54 percent reported it was unchanged and 26 
percent said it was down that compared with 19 percent reporting 
higher production in july 58 percent reporting it was unchanged 
and 23 percent saying it had slowed 
new orders dropped for the second straight month twentyone 
percent of the purchasing managers said new orders rose during 
august while 49 percent reported they were stable and 30 percent 
reported they had declined in july 19 percent reported growth in 
new orders 53 percent reported they were the same and 28 percent 
said they had declined 
the purchasing managers said export orders also dropped as did 
imports 
prices for raw materials rose during august a reflection of 
higher energy prices resulting from the gulf crisis twentytwo 
percent of the purchasing managers said they were paying higher 
prices 68 percent said they were paying the same amount and 10 
percent said prices were down that compared with 12 percent 
reporting higher prices in july 77 reporting stable prices and 11 
percent reporting lower prices 
employment fell for the 18th straight month during august and at 
a slightly faster rate than in july nine percent of the purchasing 
executives said employment was up at their companies 68 percent 
said it was the same and 23 percent said it was down in july 13 
percent said employment was up 70 percent said it was the same and 
17 percent reported a decline 
the lone bright spot in the august report was a slowing in 
supplier deliveries which indicated companies had more orders than 
they could fill seven percent of the purchasing managers surveyed 
said supplier deliveries were slower 87 percent reported they were 
the same and 6 percent said they were faster that compared with 6 
percent who said they were slower in july 83 percent who said they 
were the same and 11 percent who said they were faster 
the purchasing managers also said inventories continued to 
decline last month 
the national association of purchasing management is a research 
and education organization with more than 33000 members 
</TEXT>
