<TEXT>
johnson amp johnson sued rival 
bristolmyers squibb co on tuesday to halt an ad campaign that 
claims aspirinfree excedrin is a better pain reliever than johnson 
amp johnsons extrastrength tylenol 
in a lawsuit filed in federal court in new york the new 
brunswickbased pharmaceutical giant charged that bristolmyers 
claims were false 
the first commercial in bristolmyers new ad campaign aired 
thursday said robert kniffin johnson amp johnsons director of 
public relations 
because both drugs contain the same dose of the pain reliever 
acetaminophen the products are equivalent pain relievers kniffin 
said 
the lawsuit challenged bristolmyers assertions that the 65 
milligrams of caffeine in excedrin increase the effectiveness of 
acetaminophen he said 
it also accused bristolmyers of publishing misleading 
conclusions from three studies in which patients were asked to 
compare the effects of extrastrength tylenol versus aspirinfree 
excedrin 
officials at new yorkbased bristolmyers were not in their 
offices early tuesday evening and could not be reached for comment 
</TEXT>
